# The @media Rule üìè

Media queries let you define diverse style rules for different media types/devices.

They check things like:
- width and height of the viewport
- width and height of the device
- orientation (is the tablet/phone in landscape or portrait mode?)
- resolution

```css
@media screen and (max-width: 600px) {
  body {
    background-color: lightblue;
  }
}
```

# Breakpoints üß±

Pixels where the layout changes are called "breakpoints".

Common Breakpoints:
- **Mobile:** max-width: 600px
- **Tablet:** max-width: 768px
- **Laptop:** max-width: 992px
- **Large:** min-width: 1200px

```css
/* On screens that are 600px wide or less */
@media screen and (max-width: 600px) {
  .column {
    width: 100%;
  }
}
```

# Mobile First üì±

"Mobile  First" means designing for mobile before designing for desktop or any other device. This makes the page display faster on smaller devices.

Instead of changing styles when the width gets *smaller* (`max-width`), we change them when the width gets *larger* (`min-width`).

```css
/* Default (Mobile) styles */
.col { width: 100%; }

/* Tablet */
@media only screen and (min-width: 600px) {
  .col { width: 50%; }
}

/* Desktop */
@media only screen and (min-width: 768px) {
  .col { width: 33.33%; }
}
```

# Orientation üîÑ

Media queries can also be used to change layout depending on the orientation of the browser.

```css
@media only screen and (orientation: landscape) {
  body {
    background-color: lightblue;
  }
}
```

Useful for hiding/showing elements when a user rotates their phone.

# Hiding Elements üôà

Sometimes you want to hide elements on smaller screens (like a large sidebar).

```css
@media screen and (max-width: 600px) {
  .sidebar {
    display: none;
  }
}
```

This completely removes it from the layout.

# Responsive Typography üî†

You can use media queries to adjust font sizes.

```css
h1 {
  font-size: 80px;
}

@media screen and (max-width: 600px) {
  h1 {
    font-size: 30px;
  }
}
```

Or use viewport units: `font-size: 10vw;` (10% of viewport width).
